  "response": "One of the most tragic train accidents in history is the Balvano train disaster, which occurred on March 2, 1944, in Italy during World War II. Approximately 426-600 people died when a freight train carrying Italian soldiers and civilians stalled in the Armi tunnel near Balvano, Basilicata. The train was powered by a coal-burning steam locomotive, and carbon monoxide poisoning caused by the confined space of the tunnel led to the mass casualties. Most victims died in their sleep from the toxic fumes, making it one of the deadliest train accidents in history.\n\nAnother very tragic train accident is the Eschede train disaster in Germany on June 3, 1998, where a high-speed train derailed, killing 101 people and injuring many more. This accident was caused by a technical failure in a wheel that led to a catastrophic derailment.\n\nThese are just two examples of tragic train accidents, but there have been many others throughout history with significant loss of life.",
